        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer37654791" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1536092263369220209">one of my favorite alice hoffman books, aside from &quot;the river king&quot;. her old stuff is soooooooo much better than the new.<br/><br/>so. much. better.<br/><br/>anyhow, it takes place on the vineyard, which was excellent, becuase i could picture everything in my brain. also, her imagery and prose is aMAZing; it&apos;s like one really long poem, rahter than a novel. the characers are facinating too--they are flawed, but you love them, and you hurt for them, and you wish they were actual people that lived next door. and then</span>
  <span id="freeText1536092263369220209" style="display:none">one of my favorite alice hoffman books, aside from "the river king". her old stuff is soooooooo much better than the new.<br /><br />so. much. better.<br /><br />anyhow, it takes place on the vineyard, which was excellent, becuase i could picture everything in my brain. also, her imagery and prose is aMAZing; it's like one really long poem, rahter than a novel. the characers are facinating too--they are flawed, but you love them, and you hurt for them, and you wish they were actual people that lived next door. and then you cry when everyone is redeemed, but not in a squishy-free love sort of way. in a real way. <br /><br />p.s. sometimes i get way too into books. <br /><br />anyhow, it has hoffman's signature mystical aura, but unlike her later works, it kind of takes a back seat to the character development. i loved it, and will read it again.<br /><br />fin. </span>
